# Terminal + .venv workflow (Windows PowerShell)

## Create venv (once per repo)
From repo root (PowerShell):
- `python -m venv .venv`
  - If `python` isn't available, check your Python installation (python.org installer or winget).

## Activate venv
- `.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1`
  - If execution policy blocks this, run: `Set-ExecutionPolicy -Scope CurrentUser -ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned`

## Install deps
- `python -m pip install --upgrade pip`
- `python -m pip install -r requirements.txt`

## Run code
- Prefer:
  - Activate venv, then `python -m <module>` / `python <script>`
- Or call venv python explicitly:
  - `.venv\Scripts\python <script>`

## Tests
- `python -m pytest -q` (if pytest is used in the repo)

## Deactivate venv
- `deactivate`
